## Pubic `nthSmallest` Method

```java-hide-clipboard
    public static int nthSmallest(Tree tree, int color, int position) {
        ArrayList<Integer> nodes = new ArrayList<Integer>();
        nthSmallest(tree.getRoot(), color, nodes);
        return nodes.get(position - 1);
    }
```

* To find the $n^{th}$ smallest value in a Red-Black tree, create the public `nthSmallest` method.
* This method takes a `Tree` object, an integer representing the color (either `1` for red or `0` for black), and an integer representing the $n^{th}$ position.
* Create an empty ArrayList of integers. Since we are working with a tree structure, we are going to recursively solve this problem.
* Call the recursive `nthSmallest` method (see below) and pass it the node of the tree, the color, and the ArrayList.
* Return the element at index `position - 1`.

## Private `nthSmallest` Method

```java-hide-clipboard
    private static void nthSmallest(Node n, int color, ArrayList<Integer> nodes) {
        if (n != null) {
            nthSmallest(n.getLeft(), color, nodes);
            if (n.getColor() == color) {
                nodes.add(n.getValue());
            }
            nthSmallest(n.getRight(), color, nodes);
        }
    }
```

* The private `nthSmallest` method takes a `Node` object, an integer representing the color and an ArrayList of integers.
* The method does not return a value.
* As long as the `Node` object is not `null` first recurse down the left subtree.
* If the color of the node matches the expected color, add it to the ArrayList.
* Then recurse down the right subtree.
* We are using a pre-order traversal so the values will be placed in the ArrayList in ascending order.
